         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s20">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Nowadays, even smal=
l-scale, awards-season darlings like 2009=E2=80=99s <i>Brothers </i>or 2012=
=E2=80=99s <i>Killing Them Softly </i>are endangered species. Disney buried=
 <i>Nightbitch</i>, Searchlight=E2=80=99s <b>Amy Adams</b> vehicle, in just=
 82 theaters without reporting its official gross. Warner Bros. recently di=
d the same with <b>Clint Eastwood</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Juror #2</i>, for which =
it faced much fire-and-brimstone condemnation. <br/><br/>Instead, this time=
 of year we periodically get smaller-scale Christmas genre flicks (mostly f=
rom Universal, natch), like the horror title <i>Krampus </i>in 2015 and the=
 <i>Die Hard</i>-meets-Santa actioner <i>Violent Night </i>in 2022. Next ye=
ar=E2=80=99s attempt will be Universal=E2=80=99s <i>Five Nights at Freddy=
=E2=80=99s 2, </i>a Blumhouse video game adaptation targeted at Gen Z that =
will probably shatter records for an opening weekend on this
frame=E2=80=94even if it earns less in its first three days than last year=
=E2=80=99s $80 million-opening predecessor.<br/><br/>Still, that franchise =
is highly fan-driven and demographically specific, leaving room for another=
 big or biggish movie. Indeed, the lesson from the #Barbenheimer phenomenon=
, as well as the concurrent successes of <i>Moana 2 </i>and <i>Wicked: Part=
 One</i>, is that Hollywood should offer <i>more</i> must-see movies, espec=
ially if they don=E2=80=99t target identical demographics.  <br/><br/>In fa=
ct, this should have been clear as far back as 2003. That fall, Warner Bros=
=2E released <i>The Last Samurai</i>=
, <b>Tom Cruise</b>=E2=80=99s ambitious p=
eriod action-melodrama directed by <b>Ed Zwick</b>, the week after Thanksgi=
ving. That film ultimately earned $456 million worldwide and netted an Osca=
r nomination for <b>Ken Watanabe</b>, thriving alongside New Line=E2=80=99s=
 <i>The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King, </i>which opened weeks l=
ater and became the second movie to top $1
billion globally. Indeed, <i>two</i> big-budget period adventure epics from=
 the same parent company debuted almost on top of each other and were both =
top-tier theatrical smash hits. Two decades later, however, <i>The Last Sam=
urai </i>remains almost alone among big movies to be scheduled in this supp=
osedly doom-and-gloom window.  <br/><br/>Alas, we=E2=80=99re in a strange m=
oment now where, as the theatrical business has become imperiled, studios h=
ave tended toward risk-averse or copycat behaviors when <i>precisely the</i=
> <i>opposite </i>is required. After all, Warners now treats the <i>post</i=
>-Labor Day weekend as its preferred multi-quadrant horror movie slot=E2=80=
=94specifically because it rolled the dice in 2017 with <i>It: Chapter One<=
/i>, which snagged a $123 million domestic debut. Likewise, Disney opened <=
i>Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings </i>on Labor Day weekend in 202=
1 to $94 million=E2=80=94triple the previous Friday-Monday record (<b>Rob Z=
ombie</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Halloween
</i>remake, with $30.6 million in 2007).  <br/><br/>Studios are leaving mon=
ey on the table if they ignore what has repeatedly proven to be valuable op=
ening-weekend real estate. The sooner they realize this, the more reason we=
=E2=80=99ll have to hope that something big hits theaters on December 5, 20=
25. I mean, big for people who need to kill a couple of hours after droppin=
g their kids off at <i>Five Nights at Freddy=E2=80=99s 2</i>.<br/></td>
         </tr>
